In mainland Bolivia, the memory of the loss of the coast in a bloody dispute over natural resources with Chile in the 19th century is still alive – as is the longing for a re-navigation of the Pacific Ocean.
This hope is perhaps the greatest in decades now, as Bolivia is waiting for the decision of the International Court of Justice, which will be received after five years of consultations on 1 October.
“Bolivia has a drive, a spirit of unity and impartiality, and of course, in a positive spirit, it expects results,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will look at the International Court of Justice’s decision on the country’s big screens and hope that the court in The Hague will decide in favor of Bolivia, which claims that after decades of volatile talks, Chile must negotiate Bolivia’s access to sovereign access to the sea.
