“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court will not decide in favor of Bolivia – and even if it did, not much would change.
The Netherlands-based UN body does not have the authority to allocate Chilean territory to Bolivia, and will not decide on the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice’s decision comes just six months after the final arguments were heard means that the case “wasn’t complicated,” said Paz Z<0xC3><0xA1>rate, a Chilean expert on international law.
