John Edward: Knowledge of languages is crucial for global citizens
Scottish independent schools enjoy a reputation for academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding exam results, further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools want to prepare their students for further and higher education, a chosen career path and a place they have as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can design and implement a customized school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable elective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the conversation is imprinted on his memory.
But if you talk to a man in his mother tongue, the words are imprinted in his heart.”
This is a good reminder that we should not rely solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s results from recent exams show that languages are at the top of the rankings with the highest levels of achievement in independent schools.
68% of students who have studied a foreign language have achieved excellent grades.
Data collected in 74 schools of the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS) showed that 72 per cent of students achieved an excellent score in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of students of German, 69 per cent of students of French and 63 per cent of students of Spanish had an excellent score.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as the key knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are treated as an elective subject in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere in the same way as subjects in the fields of science, technology, engineering and mathematics.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Training Commission found that 17 per cent of the reasons employers are struggling to fill their jobs can be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, knowledge of languages is becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future career path.
For future job opportunities that require language skills, these skills are essential in the global world.
If someone learns a different language, regardless of the career path he chooses, with such lifelong knowledge, he has a great advantage in the future.
A multilingual person, who can communicate directly with people from foreign countries, has an automatic advantage over the competition.
A 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK found that 75 percent of people didn’t speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak, with French being the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of respondents, that’s 15 percent.
Therefore, investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
With the knowledge of several languages, especially those from countries with a developing economy, children have a better chance of finding a suitable job.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important to the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of your child, in independent schools it will always be possible to choose a number of languages taught by experts in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the knowledge they need to succeed, no matter what the future brings.
In the global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages remain extremely important for the future of the country, and this must also be expressed in education.
In fact, modern languages should be treated as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
