North Korea: “Without trust, we will not unilaterally disarm”
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continued implementation of the sanctions is causing growing mistrust in the United States and that under such conditions North Korea will certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Jong Ho, at the annual meeting of the General Assembly of this world body, said that North Korea had taken a number of “significant measures in the past year in the name of goodwill” such as halting nuclear and missile tests, undermining the site for nuclear tests, and making no promises of nuclear weapons.
“We don’t see a proper response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we will not be confident in national security, and under such conditions, we will not unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament, under which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual action, his statement was significant because he did not immediately reject the unilateral refusal to do so.
Ri cited a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump from the first summit between the current U.S. president and the North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12. At the time, Kim pledged to strive for “nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump assured the North Korean side of caution.
North Korea wants an official end to the Korean War, which took place between 1950 and 1953, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up nuclear weapons.
Washington has also not given up on calls for the release of the strict international sanctions that apply to North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that we must first denuclearize, and it is stepping up the pressure of sanctions to achieve its goals by force, and it is even objecting to the declaration of an end to the war,” Ri said.
“Thinking that sanctions could bring us to our knees is an unrealistic hope for people who don’t even know us.
The problem, however, is that the further implementation of sanctions further deepens our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the US president outlined at the United Nations General Assembly earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in that have taken place over the past five months, adding: “If we were to talk about the nuclear disarmament problem with South Korea and not with the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not be dead.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri’s speech was completely different from that of last year, when the United Nations General Assembly said that an attack on the mainland of the United States with North Korean missiles was inevitable, after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, at the United Nations General Assembly praised Kim and his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still a lot of work to do and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is overthrown.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no time frame for this, saying, “It can take two years, three years, or five months — it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia are of the opinion that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of sanctions by the Security Council must resolutely continue without exception until we recognize the full, final and verified state of nuclear disarmament.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously adopted additional sanctions on North Korea to prevent the financing of North Korea’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Russia on the sidelines of the United Nations General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for the second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not end well.
When he left Pyongyang in July, he said progress had been made, and North Korea had already criticised him for saying his demands were “gangster.”
North Korea pledged at a meeting with Moon earlier this month that it would demolish a missile test station and nuclear test infrastructure if the United States took “appropriate action.”
Mr Moon said the "appropriate measures" meant the security assurances Trump had promised in Singapore and measures to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard University students attend a course where they learn how to take enough time to rest
The goal of this year’s new course at Harvard University is for all undergraduate students to learn how to afford more sleep. With such a course, they want to fight against the growing masculinity culture of “full-time” learning, in which the powers are built up with caffeine.
A university professor has found that students at the world’s best universities often don’t know the basics about caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women's Hospital, designed the course, which is the first of its kind in the United States.
To carry out such a course, he decided after his lecture on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl approached him and said, “Why do I only know this now that I’m in my last year?”
She said no one had told her how important sleep was, and the professor told The Daily Telegraph that he was surprised.
The course, which is being conducted for the first time this year, talks about the key importance of good sleep habits for study and sports success as well as for improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health services, says they decided to take such a course when they found that the student was significantly lacking in sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of the door of the student home, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books to get information on the impact of caffeine and light, the impact of lack of sleep on sports success and the importance of sleep routine.
In the second section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The map of the student settlement with interactive icons of the participants encourages you to think about their daily routine.
“We know that students’ behavior will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know these facts, just as they have the right to know how their health is affected by cigarette smoking,” adds Professor Czeisler.
The professor says that a culture of pride is still present in “surviving all-night learning”. He also adds that modern technology and the growing pressure on students, as a result of which lack of sleep, represent growing problems.
Professor Czeisler says that a sufficient amount of quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety. Thus, they can also avoid gaining weight – the brain, due to lack of sleep, goes into a mode of hunger, which makes them lazy.
19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology Raymond So helped Professor Czeisler design the course. Last year, during his first year at Harvard, he attended one of the professor’s lectures.
He says that the lecture opened his eyes and encouraged him to carry out the course throughout the student settlement.
He hopes that in the next phase, postgraduate students will be able to ask to complete a similar study program before enrolling in a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set their alarm clock to sleep as well as to wake up. He also wants to warn them of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, as they can cause an imbalance in the circadian rhythm, which is what makes it so.
