News of the red tide: Concentrations on the coasts of Pinellas, Manatee and Saratosa counties are decreasing
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
The FWC reported more widespread flowering in the Pinellas, Manatee, Saratosa, Charlotte and Collier districts, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide stretches approximately 130 miles from the coast north of Pinellas County to the southern counties of Lee.
The billboards are visible about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, medium concentrations were reported in Pinellas County and along its coast, low-to-high concentrations on the coast of Hillsborough County, low-to-high concentrations in Manatee County, low-to-high concentrations in Saratosa County and along its coast, low-to-high concentrations in Charlotte County, and low-to-high concentrations in County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation from Northwest Florida in the past week.
